Interview gold answer 😎

Instead of handling everything inside method_missing forever (which is slow), we can:

Use method_missing only the first time

Dynamically define the getter & setter using define_method

Next time, Ruby calls the real method directly (no method_missing)

That’s how Rails internally optimizes things too.

🧠 Why define_method is Better

method_missing runs every time → slower
define_method creates a real method → fast after first call

✅ Clean Solution Using define_method
class User
  def initialize(name)
    @name = name
  end

  def greet
    puts "Hello #{@name}"
  end

  def method_missing(method_name, *args, &block)
    method_name = method_name.to_s

    if method_name.end_with?("=")
      # Setter
      attribute = method_name.chomp("=")

      # Define setter method dynamically
      self.class.define_method(method_name) do |value|
        instance_variable_set("@#{attribute}", value)
      end

      # Define getter method dynamically
      self.class.define_method(attribute) do
        instance_variable_get("@#{attribute}")
      end

      # Call the newly defined setter
      send(method_name, args.first)

      nil
    else
      super
    end
  end

  def respond_to_missing?(method_name, include_private = false)
    true
  end
end
🔎 Test It
x = User.new("Shubham")

x.demo = "abc"
# => nil

x.demo
# => "abc"

x.demo
# => "abc"   (Now it doesn't go to method_missing)

After first call:

demo=

demo

are REAL methods on the class.

🧠 How It Works Internally
1️⃣ x.demo = "abc"

Ruby calls:

method_missing(:demo=, "abc")
2️⃣ We dynamically define:
def demo=(value)
  @demo = value
end

def demo
  @demo
end
3️⃣ Then we call:
send("demo=", "abc")

Now real method runs.

🔥 Important Detail

We used:

instance_variable_set("@#{attribute}", value)

Because attribute name is dynamic.

Same for getter:

instance_variable_get("@#{attribute}")
⚡ Performance Difference
Approach	Performance
Only method_missing	Slow (always dynamic lookup)
method_missing + define_method	Fast after first call

This shows senior-level thinking in interview.

🎯 Even Cleaner Version (Pro Level)

If interviewer allows:

def method_missing(method_name, *args)
  name = method_name.to_s

  if name.end_with?("=")
    attr = name.chomp("=")
    self.class.attr_accessor attr
    send(method_name, args.first)
  else
    super
  end
end

That’s even more elegant 😄

